            "description": "",
            "details": "<p><em>Ḥīretü’l-beyżā</em>: This is also one of the cities of <em>‘Irāḳ</em> (Iraq), lying about one farsakh from <em>Kūfe</em> (Kufa). In the age of ignorance (<em>zamān-ı cāhiliyye</em>), it was a highly prosperous place. When Münẕir bin Ümerā’i’l-Ḳays gained victory over his enemies in this town, he restored it and had great churches (<em>kenā’is-i ‘aẓīme</em>) built there. According to some, the town now called <em>Necef</em> (Najaf) stands on the site of this former settlement. Others say that it was located on the shore of the <em>Baḥr-i Fārs</em> (Persian Gulf); this, too, is reported. It is also narrated that when one of the <em>Tübbā‘</em> of Yemen traveled toward <em>Ḫorāsān</em> (Khorasan), he halted at a certain spot for the night, and the next day constructed a town there and named it <em>Ḥīre</em>. It is said that the <em>Ḳaṣr-ı Ḥavernaḳ</em> (Palace of Khavarnaq) is also located there, which was the residence of Nu‘mān bin Münẕir. [translation]</p>",
